      Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.Ga=
meStopLook the very standard corporate finance theory is that it=E2=80=99s =
good for a company if its stock price goes up. A company can issue stock; i=
t can, in a sense, make as much as it wants of its own stock for free. If t=
hat stock is worth a lot and keeps going up, it can do things with it. It c=
an sell the stock for=C2=A0money and use the money to do business things. C=
ompanies usually=C2=A0pay executives largely in stock, and if a company=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0stock keeps going up then it will be able to attract and retai=
n good talented executives because good people will want to be paid in good=
 stock. Employees who own stock will be happy and motivated and will do bet=
ter work because they keep getting richer.[1] Companies often pay for acqui=
sitions in stock, and, again, having an attractive currency lets a company =
do attractive acquisitions.=C2=A0Usually all this stuff=C2=A0lives in sort =
of an obvious feedback loop: You do good business things, your stock goes u=
p, this allows you to do more good business things, etc. If you just, like,=
 exogenously discovered a gigantic pile of diamonds in the basement of your=
 headquarters, that might make your stock price go up, but would it make yo=
u better at doing your business? You could call up superstar executives and=
 say =E2=80=9Chey come work for our company, we just found a bunch of diamo=
nds=E2=80=9D; would they do it? I don=E2=80=99t know! Maybe? It=E2=80=99s a=
 weird question. There are not a lot of natural experiments.My Bloomberg Op=
inion colleague  Tae Kim writes=C2=A0about GameStop Corp.:GameStop Inc. has=
 been best known lately for the excitement it has generated with the Reddit=
 crowd, and as one of the first of the big meme-stock winners. But for thos=
e willing to take a deeper look, there is something more going on: Its prom=
ised transformation is taking shape and making significant progress.On Wedn=
esday, the video-game retailer filled out the remaining key openings for it=
s senior-management team by hiring a new chief executive officer and chief =
financial officer =E2=80=94 both from Amazon.com Inc. GameStop also reporte=
d strong earnings and revealed a plan to raise more capital. Most of the ha=
rd work is still ahead, but these are all big positives.The biographies of =
the new leaders give more credibility to GameStop=E2=80=99s turnaround stra=
tegy. The company appointed Matt Furlong as CEO and Mike Recupero as CFO, b=
oth of whom supervised growth operations for Amazon. Most recently, Furlong=
 led the e-commerce giant=E2=80=99s Australia business, while Recupero serv=
ed as CFO of Amazon=E2=80=99s North American consumer business. Their backg=
rounds are in stark contrast to GameStop=E2=80=99s current CEO, whose prior=
 stint entailed running a retail business for that sold Verizon Wireless pr=
oducts and services, and its former CFO =E2=80=94 who previously was an exe=
cutive at a Chinese restaurant chain.A year ago, GameStop=E2=80=99s stock c=
losed at $5.07 per share, down 7% year-over-year, and it was not hiring=C2=
=A0talent from Amazon or raising a billion dollars by selling stock. Yester=
day, GameStop=E2=80=99s stock closed at $302.56, up 5,867% year-over-year, =
and it is. The stock price is not the=C2=A0only=C2=A0thing that has changed=
: Ryan Cohen, the Chewy Inc. founder who came to GameStop as an activist in=
vestor and is now its board chair, has a turnaround plan and an ability to =
attract executives. And the stock price has not changed=C2=A0entirely=C2=A0=
exogenously; Cohen and his plan, and the early steps toward executing it, h=
ave helped the stock. But, uh, you know. This is as close as you=E2=80=99re=
 ever going to come to a company=E2=80=99s stock going up 5,000% in a few m=
onths for no reason. Seems like that might be good for business!=C2=A0GameS=
top=E2=80=99s annual shareholder meeting was yesterday, and its new chairma=
n spoke:Mr. Cohen said at the meeting that the company was fortunate to hav=
e such a special group of investors holding its shares. =E2=80=9CYou guys i=
nspire us to think bigger, fight harder and work longer each day,=E2=80=9D =
he said, adding that the investors have ushered in a whole new era at GameS=
top.I think that=E2=80=99s right: By paying a ton of money for GameStop sto=
ck, its shareholders have inspired its executives to work harder (and hire =
better executives). They have=C2=A0inspired those executives to think bigge=
r; if you run a $20 billion company you will naturally make bigger plans th=
an if you run a $300 million company. They have certainly ushered in a whol=
e new era at GameStop: the era in which it is a meme stock with an enormous=
 valuation. Perhaps also an era in which it justifies that valuation.Or may=
be this is the peak, I don=E2=80=99t know;=C2=A0the stock was  down this mo=
rning because of the stock offering and a Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n probe about its trading.Archegos CubsHuh:Just three months after investor=
 Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s investment firm imploded =E2=80=94 leaving Wall Stree=
t with billions of dollars in losses =E2=80=94 two Archegos Capital staffer=
s are gearing up to test the strategy all over again, The Post has learned.=
Jensen Ko and Sterling Clay, who worked at Archegos until its epic collapse=
 in March, are quietly preparing to launch a new fund using their former bo=
ss=E2=80=99s highly leveraged investment style, people with direct knowledg=
e of the plans told The Post.=E2=80=9CThe strategy worked until it didn=E2=
=80=99t=E2=80=A6. but it worked,=E2=80=9D a source close to one of the Arch=
egos alumni told The Post in explaining their thinking.Ko and Clay plan to =
use their own money over the next year to establish a track record of lucra=
tive but reliable investments with the goal of eventually raising money fro=
m outside investors, according to people with direct knowledge.=C2=A0 =E2=
=80=A6The Post was unable to confirm how much the pair have to invest, but =
people close to them estimated it could be close to $50 million. =E2=80=A6=
=E2=80=9CI think being an alumnus of Archegos will make it difficult,=E2=80=
=9D Columbia University Law School professor John Coffee tells The Post. =
=E2=80=9CIt is a little like having been the lookout on the Titanic and app=
lying for similar work.=E2=80=9DWhat=C2=A0was=C2=A0Archegos=E2=80=99s strat=
egy? I still don=E2=80=99t exactly know, but I think there are=C2=A0two pos=
sibilities. One is: You borrow a ton of money to buy a handful of stocks, y=
our buying activity pushes the stocks up, your positions are worth more so =
you can borrow more against them, and you plow the additional borrowed mone=
y into buying more of your stocks. You keep pushing up the price, giving yo=
u paper profits but continuing to run the slimmest possible cushion of equi=
ty, until a slight breeze knocks the whole thing over.This is  how I descri=
bed Archegos shortly after it collapsed, and it is a=C2=A0bad=C2=A0strategy=
. =E2=80=9CIt worked until it didn=E2=80=99t, but it worked=E2=80=9D misund=
erstands the problem with this strategy. This is a strategy of doubling dow=
n after every bet you win; it can work for a while but it will always end b=
y not working.The other possibility is: You borrow a ton of money, non-reco=
urse of course; you build risky concentrated positions in a handful of stoc=
ks using that borrowed money; you try to pick stocks that go up. If they go=
 up, you call your brokers and say =E2=80=9Chey I notice we have big paper =
profits, please send a check for those profits.=E2=80=9D And then you cash =
the check and put the money somewhere safe and out of reach of your brokers=
.=C2=A0If they go down, your brokers call you and say =E2=80=9Chey I notice=
 you have big losses, please send some money for a margin call,=E2=80=9D an=
d you say =E2=80=9Chow did you get this number?=E2=80=9D And you close your=
 fund and open a fresh one three months later.I  suggested earlier this wee=
k that this=C2=A0might=C2=A0have been Archegos=E2=80=99s strategy, and it i=
s a good strategy. The fact that Ko and Clay=C2=A0have $50 million in their=
 personal accounts after Archegos went to zero=C2=A0suggests that this migh=
t have been the strategy?=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt worked until it didn=E2=80=99t, =
but it worked=E2=80=9D would be great, if when it worked you took the profi=
ts, and when it didn=E2=80=99t your banks ate the losses.I  said last month=
 that =E2=80=9Ca somewhat tongue-in-cheek but surprisingly useful maxim of =
high finance is that it is good for your career if you lose a billion dolla=
rs.=E2=80=9D Archegos cost its banks some $10 billion of losses, and the fu=
nd itself lost some multiple of that peak to trough, and how can you not be=
 a little impressed by that? =E2=80=9CYou have probably learned from your m=
istake and won=E2=80=99t do it again,=E2=80=9D I said about career-enhancin=
g losses, and what lessons did these guys learn? Like if you are a potentia=
l investor in their next fund, how does that interview go?Investor: So you =
lost like $30 billion?Ko: Well $10 billion of that was the banks=E2=80=99 m=
oney, but yes.Investor: I assume you learned some lessons from that debacle=
?Clay: Yes, all the good lessons.Investor: What lessons specifically?Ko:=C2=
=A0Definitely make sure all your leverage is non-recourse.Clay: Also do eve=
rything on swap so that you don=E2=80=99t have to disclose and nobody knows=
 what you=E2=80=99re up to.Right? Like, structurally there is a lot to be s=
aid for the Archegos trade; really the only problem is that the stocks went=
 down. I bet they=E2=80=99ll get investors.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know who w=
ill want to be their prime broker though?=C2=A0


