10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight=
: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;=
 letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0=
;">GameStop</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look the very standard corpora=
te finance theory is that it=E2=80=99s good for a company if its stock pric=
e goes up. A company can issue stock; it can, in a sense, make as much as i=
t wants of its own stock for free. If that stock is worth a lot and keeps g=
oing up, it can do things with it. It can sell the stock for=C2=A0money and=
 use the money to do business things. Companies usually=C2=A0pay executives=
 largely in stock, and if a company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock keeps going up the=
n it will be able to attract and retain good talented executives because go=
od people will want to be paid in good stock. Employees who own stock will =
be happy and motivated and will do better work because they keep getting ri=
cher.[1] Companies often pay for acquisitions in stock, and, again, having =
an attractive currency lets a company do attractive acquisitions.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually all this stuff=C2=A0lives in sort of a=
n obvious feedback loop: You do good business things, your stock goes up, t=
his allows you to do more good business things, etc. If you just, like, exo=
genously discovered a gigantic pile of diamonds in the basement of your hea=
dquarters, that might make your stock price go up, but would it make you be=
tter at doing your business? You could call up superstar executives and say=
 =E2=80=9Chey come work for our company, we just found a bunch of diamonds=
=E2=80=9D; would they do it? I don=E2=80=99t know! Maybe? It=E2=80=99s a we=
ird question. There are not a lot of natural experiments.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">My Bloomberg Opinion colleague <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvZ2FtZXN0b3Atcy1sYXRlc3QtYW1hem9uLW=
hpcmVzLXNob3ctaXQtcy1ub3QtanVzdC1yZWRkaXQtbWVtZS1zdG9jaw/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB575d0c53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> Tae Kim writes</a>=C2=A0about GameStop Corp.:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameStop Inc. has been best known lately for the exc=
itement it has generated with the Reddit crowd, and as one of the first of =
the big meme-stock winners. But for those willing to take a deeper look, th=
ere is something more going on: Its promised transformation is taking shape=
 and making significant progress.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Wednes=
day, the video-game retailer filled out the remaining key openings for its =
senior-management team by hiring a new chief executive officer and chief fi=
nancial officer =E2=80=94 both from Amazon.com Inc. GameStop also reported =
strong earnings and revealed a plan to raise more capital. Most of the hard=
 work is still ahead, but these are all big positives.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">The biographies of the new leaders give more credibility to Gam=
eStop=E2=80=99s turnaround strategy. The company appointed Matt Furlong as =
CEO and Mike Recupero as CFO, both of whom supervised growth operations for=
 Amazon. Most recently, Furlong led the e-commerce giant=E2=80=99s Australi=
a business, while Recupero served as CFO of Amazon=E2=80=99s North American=
 consumer business. Their backgrounds are in stark contrast to GameStop=E2=
=80=99s current CEO, whose prior stint entailed running a retail business f=
or that sold Verizon Wireless products and services, and its former CFO =E2=
=80=94 who previously was an executive at a Chinese restaurant chain.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A year ago, GameStop=E2=80=99s stoc=
k closed at $5.07 per share, down 7% year-over-year, and it was not <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTMyNjM4MC8wMDAxMTkz=
MTI1MjExODY3MzIvZDE3NDQwMGQ4ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB13d3ab17" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">hiring=C2=A0ta=
lent</a> from Amazon or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhL=
zEzMjYzODAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMTg2Nzk2L2QxOTI4NzNkNDI0YjUuaHRt/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB463aef25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">raising a billion dollars by selling stock</a>. Yesterday, GameSt=
op=E2=80=99s stock closed at $302.56, up 5,867% year-over-year, and it is. =
The stock price is not the=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>thing that has changed: =
Ryan Cohen, the Chewy Inc. founder who came to GameStop as an activist inve=
stor and is now its board chair, has a turnaround plan and an ability to at=
tract executives. And the stock price has not changed=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=
=A0</em>exogenously; Cohen and his plan, and the early steps toward executi=
ng it, have helped the stock. But, uh, you know. This is as close as you=E2=
=80=99re ever going to come to a company=E2=80=99s stock going up 5,000% in=
 a few months for no reason. Seems like that might be good for business!=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameStop=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLm=
dvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTMyNjM4MC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjExODY3N=
TkvZDE3NDM0MGQ4ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC6f7abf5b" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">annual shareholder meeting<=
/a> was yesterday, and its new chairman spoke:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Mr. Cohen said at the meeting that the company was fortunat=
e to have such a special group of investors holding its shares. =E2=80=9CYo=
u guys inspire us to think bigger, fight harder and work longer each day,=
=E2=80=9D he said, adding that the investors have ushered in a whole new er=
a at GameStop.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that=E2=
=80=99s right: By paying a ton of money for GameStop stock, its shareholder=
s have inspired its executives to work harder (and hire better executives).=
 They have=C2=A0inspired those executives to think bigger; if you run a $20=
 billion company you will naturally make bigger plans than if you run a $30=
0 million company. They have certainly ushered in a whole new era at GameSt=
op: the era in which it is a meme stock with an enormous valuation. Perhaps=
 also an era in which it justifies that valuation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Or maybe this is the peak, I don=E2=80=99t know;=C2=A0the stock was=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvZ2FtZXN0=
b3Atc2xpZGVzLW9uLXN0b2NrLXNhbGUtcGxhbi1zZWMtdHJhZGluZy1pbnZlc3RpZ2F0aW9u/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBebf48abd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> down this morning</a> because of the stock offering=
 and a Securities and Exchange Commission probe about its trading.</p><h2 s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Hel=
vetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30p=
x; margin-bottom: 0;">Archegos Cubs</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9ueXBvc3QuY29tLzIwMjEvMDYvMDgvcHJvdGVnZXMtb2YtYmlsbC1od2FuZy1iZWhpbmQtZXB=
pYy1hcmNoZWdvcy1jb2xsYXBzZS1wbGFuLW5ldy1mdW5kLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c=
db9e52" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Hu=
h</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just three months after =
investor Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s investment firm imploded =E2=80=94 leaving Wa=
ll Street with billions of dollars in losses =E2=80=94 two Archegos Capital=
 staffers are gearing up to test the strategy all over again, The Post has =
learned.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jensen Ko and Sterling Clay, who w=
orked at Archegos until its epic collapse in March, are quietly preparing t=
o launch a new fund using their former boss=E2=80=99s highly leveraged inve=
stment style, people with direct knowledge of the plans told The Post.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe strategy worked until it didn=E2=
=80=99t=E2=80=A6. but it worked,=E2=80=9D a source close to one of the Arch=
egos alumni told The Post in explaining their thinking.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Ko and Clay plan to use their own money over the next year to =
establish a track record of lucrative but reliable investments with the goa=
l of eventually raising money from outside investors, according to people w=
ith direct knowledge.=C2=A0 =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The P=
ost was unable to confirm how much the pair have to invest, but people clos=
e to them estimated it could be close to $50 million. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI think being an alumnus of Archegos will mak=
e it difficult,=E2=80=9D Columbia University Law School professor John Coff=
ee tells The Post. =E2=80=9CIt is a little like having been the lookout on =
the Titanic and applying for similar work.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>Archegos=E2=80=99s strate=
gy? I still don=E2=80=99t exactly know, but I think there are=C2=A0two poss=
ibilities. One is: You borrow a ton of money to buy a handful of stocks, yo=
ur buying activity pushes the stocks up, your positions are worth more so y=
ou can borrow more against them, and you plow the additional borrowed money=
 into buying more of your stocks. You keep pushing up the price, giving you=
 paper profits but continuing to run the slimmest possible cushion of equit=
y, until a slight breeze knocks the whole thing over.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">This is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhc=
mQtZm9yLWJhbmtz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb063d5f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> how I described Archegos</a> shor=
tly after it collapsed, and it is a=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>strategy. =E2=80=
=9CIt worked until it didn=E2=80=99t, but it worked=E2=80=9D misunderstands=
 the problem with this strategy. This is a strategy of doubling down after =
every bet you win; it can work for a while but it will <em>always </em>end =
by not working.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other possibility is: Y=
ou borrow a ton of money, non-recourse of course; you build risky concentra=
ted positions in a handful of stocks using that borrowed money; you try to =
pick stocks that go up. If they go up, you call your brokers and say =E2=80=
=9Chey I notice we have big paper profits, please send a check for those pr=
ofits.=E2=80=9D And then you cash the check and put the money somewhere saf=
e and out of reach of your brokers.=C2=A0If they go down, your brokers call=
 you and say =E2=80=9Chey I notice you have big losses, please send some mo=
ney for a margin call,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Chow did you get this n=
umber?=E2=80=9D And you close your fund and open a fresh one three months l=
ater.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDgvbW92aWVwYXNzLWNoYW5nZWQtc29tZS1wYXNzd29y=
ZHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5afed1e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> suggested earlier this week</a> that this=C2=
=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>have been Archegos=E2=80=99s strategy, and it is a<e=
m> good</em> strategy. The fact that Ko and Clay=C2=A0<em>have $50 million =
in their personal accounts after Archegos went to zero</em>=C2=A0suggests t=
hat this might have been the strategy?=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt worked until it did=
n=E2=80=99t, but it worked=E2=80=9D would be great, if when it worked you t=
ook the profits, and when it didn=E2=80=99t your banks ate the losses.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24111213.276879/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjYvZXh4b24taGFzLWEtdG91Z2gtZ3JlZW4tYWN0aXZpc3Q/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB640b7e06" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> said last month</a> that =E2=80=9Ca somewhat tongue-in-=
cheek but surprisingly useful maxim of high finance is that it is good for =
your career if you lose a billion dollars.=E2=80=9D Archegos cost its banks=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24111213.276879/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy91YnMtdGFrZXMtc3VycHJpc2UtNzc0LW1pbGxp=
b24tYXJjaGVnb3MtaGl0LTExNjE5NTAxNTQ3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d635d39" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">some $10 bill=
ion of losses</a>, and the fund itself lost some multiple of that peak to t=
rough, and how can you not be a little impressed by that? =E2=80=9CYou have=
 probably learned from your mistake and won=E2=80=99t do it again,=E2=80=9D=
 I said about career-enhancing losses, and what lessons did these guys lear=
n? Like if you are a potential investor in their next fund, how does that i=
nterview go?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Investor:<=
/strong> So you lost like $30 billion?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><str=
ong>Ko:</strong> Well $10 billion of that was the banks=E2=80=99 money, but=
 yes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Investor:</strong> I assume y=
ou learned some lessons from that debacle?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
<strong>Clay:</strong> Yes, all the good lessons.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;"><strong>Investor:</strong> What lessons specifically?</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Ko:</strong>=C2=A0Definitely make sure all your l=
everage is non-recourse.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Clay:</str=
ong> Also do everything on swap so that you don=E2=80=99t have to disclose =
and nobody knows what you=E2=80=99re up to.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Right? Like, structurally there is a lot to be said for the A=
rchegos trade; really the only problem is that the stocks went down. I bet =
they=E2=80=99ll get investors.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know who will want to b=
e their prime broker though?=C2=A0</p>
